generated_encounter_updates.reason_display_text: Patient presents with pain and swelling in lower right jaw due to impacted wisdom tooth.
generated_encounter_updates.transcript:
Doctor: Hello Laura, what brings you in today?
Laura: Hi Doctor, I've been having a lot of pain in my lower right jaw for the past week, and it's swollen.
Doctor: I see. Let me take a look. (Examines mouth) It looks like your wisdom tooth is impacted and causing some inflammation. We call this pericoronitis.
Laura: Oh, is that serious?
Doctor: It can be quite uncomfortable and lead to infection if not treated. I'll prescribe some antibiotics and pain relief for now, and we'll need to get an X-ray to see its exact position. Then we can discuss options for removing the tooth.
generated_encounter_updates.soap_note:
S: Laura Ramirez, a 27 y/o female (DOB 1963-07-16), reports increasing pain and swelling in the lower right posterior jaw for 1 week. Difficulty opening mouth fully. Pain worsens with chewing.
O: Vital signs stable. Oral exam reveals inflamed, erythematous gingival tissue overlying a partially erupted tooth #32. Tender to palpation. Mild trismus.
A: Impacted lower right third molar (#32) with acute pericoronitis.
P: 1. Prescribe Amoxicillin 500mg TID for 7 days. 2. Prescribe Ibuprofen 600mg PRN for pain. 3. Advise warm salt water rinses. 4. Order panoramic X-ray. 5. Discuss referral to oral surgeon for extraction.
generated_encounter_updates.observations: Partially erupted lower right third molar with significant gingival inflammation and tenderness. Patient appears in discomfort.
